    >LDA:000021</rdfs:label>
  </owl:Class>
  <owl:Class rdf:about="http://www.semanticweb.org/ontologies/2008/10/languageacquisition_autism.owl#Phrase">
    <rdfs:label rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#ID"
    >LDA:000029</rdfs:label>
    <dc:creator>Nataliya Kostyuk</dc:creator>
    <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string"
    >Some children exhibit echolalia, which is the repetition of words, signs, phrases or sentences spoken by other people. Some children use this as a communication device (i.e. the adult says “do you want a car?” and the child might say “want a car” to mean yes.) A child may repeat the same phrase over and over again as a means of regulating their own behaviour (i.e., a child repeats aloud “time to clean up” while cleaning).
Some children may be delayed in acquiring speech, but progress eventually to form clear, fluent, well-formed sentences.  However, their speech may remain repetitive and non-communicative, and may be marked by echolalia.  That is, they may repeat back what another person says to them.They learn to talk by memorising words and phrases, while being unable to use these same words freely.Also, they 
 repeat phrases out of context, especially phrases heard on TV.</rdfs:comment>
    <dc:date rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#date"
    >12-15-2008</dc:date>
