  <owl:Class rdf:about="http://www.semanticweb.org/ontologies/2008/10/languageacquisition_autism.owl#Grammar">
    <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string"
    >Grammar - a set of generally agreed upon rules for language use in a certain community around specific tasks including punctuation, word use, sentence structure, etc.; grammar conventions may differ slightly or significantly according to audience, purpose, and context.
Children with autism show extreme difficulties interpreting reflexives, as well as short and long passives of both actional and psychological verbs. The lack of distinct pattern in the interpretation of actional versus psychological passives resembles the performance of very young children who cannot yet employ the strategy of interpreting actional passives as adjectival. Poor interpretation of reflexive but not personal pronouns suggests an inability to compute the syntactic relationship between the reflexive and its antecedent, whereas  poor performance on passives indicates an inability to interpret syntactic chains. Knowledge of important aspects of grammar is severely impaired in children with autistic developmental disorder, which contrasts the traditional observation that grammar is intact in autism.</rdfs:comment>
    <rdfs:label rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#ID"
    >LDA:000001</rdfs:label>
