    <rdfs:comment rdf:datatype="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#string"
    >Pronoun reversal is a language disability observed in the speech of children affected with autism. According to a description, pronoun reversal is when the person with autism confuses first and second person pronouns in speech.Autistic subjects are significantly less likely to employ the pronoun "me" in a visual perspective-taking task (when instead they tended to say: 'I can see the . . .'), and lower ability subjects are more likely to use their own proper names rather than personal pronouns in certain photograph-naming tasks. Autistic subjects are less likely to employ the pronoun "you". A high proportion of  autistic subjects are reported to have current difficulties with personal pronouns in their everyday life.</rdfs:comment>
